<br>
The problem is you're both assuming Nasren would have been first there IF FG's weren't reservable... I submit that's the flaw.<br>
<br>
So, Puma logged in at his raid time... well, that makes sense in a reservation environment.  Remove his somewhat 'safe' reserved raid (safe in the sense that the target might be there when he goes there) and why would he be logging in then?<br>
<br>
Realistically, without that reservation, pressure would have been there for him to potentially be there before Nasren sent in (or logged in) his alt... so no, without FG reservations there is NOTHING guaranteeing Nasren would now have his epic, other than what you wish had happened.<br>
<br>
So, yes I'm creating alternate scenarios... but so are you when you're claiming with certainty that Nasrens epic was ONLY interfered with by FG reservations... the difference is I'm acknowledging any of my scneraios may or may not have happened (which includes the possibility you are right)... you are dead set that it could only have happened ONE other way, that's simply incorrect.<br>
<br>
Nasren's point about clarifying 'who has rights' is the real issue.  It will be a real issue whether FG's are or are not reserved... the various 'possible' scenarios I outlined of what might have been included several different interpretations people could have had over 'who is right.'  THAT is the problem right now...<br>
<br>
Is it the first Cleric in the zone 'claiming camp' that has rights?  If so, why should a fully ready to roll raid WAIT on that in an FCFS environment?  It's not the standard for other FCFS... and there is certainly Epic greed on the lines... frankly I don't see that standing cleric (or other class) getting their way regularly on that one... someone will 'roll over their ragefire camp' (as quoted from another source in this thread).<br>
<br>
Is it the first raid on the scene?  How long does that raid have to be there...<br>
<br>
I don't think you'd find many Fire Giant Reservation proponents (and I'll acknowledge I'm probably the loudest of them) that would assume that a true FG raid should have precedence over Ragefire (I wouldn't and don't)... but I do think that the situation over 'who is next' wouldn't be civil in FCFS.<br>
<br>
I can think of a single guild (last memorial day weekend) that had made plans to camp Ragefire all Memorial Day weekend, and work around FG raids as needed)... drop FG reservations and that's 10 Clerics every friday (or earlier) claiming camp rights... and you thought the VS list was long... /chuckle...<br>
<br>
The real question right now shouldn't be about FG's... the real question should be among Clerics over how Ragefire should be handled on this server... once that's figured out... I suspect an easy compromise would work to appease the one Fire Giant raid every 8 to 10 days that actually wants Fire Giants... Make a Ragefire reservation (or something)... let interested Fire Giant raids (like mine) coordinate with the designated Ragefire camper... hell, I don't mind that... do something about Ragefire... and understand FCFS isn't the answer... take a long look at the number of guilds with 55+ Clerics that don't have epics... remove that FG reservation bottleneck and every single one of themm will be shooting for that camp and staying on it till every single one of their clerics has it done... if anything, this FG 'bottleneck' just mixes up the deck and gets some different folks than just members of {a guild}.<br>
<br>
But stop assigning incorrect blame, and start looking for a Ragefire solution... everything else will fall into place.<br>
<br>
